1. Niño 3.4 index¶

The Nio 3.4 anomalies may be thought of as representing the average equatorial SSTs across the Pacific from about the dateline to the South American coast (5N-5S, 170W-120W). The Nio 3.4 index typically uses a 3-month running mean, and El Nio or La Nia events are defined when the Nio 3.4 SSTs exceed +/- 0.5C for a period of 5 months or more. Check Equatorial Pacific Sea Surface Temperatures for more about the Nio 3.4 index.

In this problem set, you will use the sea surface temperature (SST) data from NOAA. Download the netCDF4 file (NOAA_NCDC_ERSST_v3b_SST.nc) here.

1.1 [5 points] Compute monthly climatology for SST from Niño 3.4 region, and subtract climatology from SST time series to obtain anomalies.¶

Download the data (CERES_EBAF-TOA_200003-201701.nc) here. The size of the data file is 702.5 MB. It will take a minute or two to download. Start by importing xarray, numpy, and matplotlib.

2.1 [5 points] Make a 2D plot of the time-mean TOA longwave, shortwave, and solar radiation for all-sky conditions. Add up the three variables above and verify (visually) that they are equivalent to the TOA net flux.¶

cet = xr.open_dataset('CERES_EBAF-TOA_200003-201701.nc')

#shortwave
shortwave = cet.toa_sw_all_mon.mean(dim='time')

#longwave
longwave = cet.toa_lw_all_mon.mean(dim='time')

#solar radiation
solar_radiation = cet.solar_mon.mean(dim='time')

#add up
lss = (cet.solar_mon - cet.toa_lw_all_mon - cet.toa_sw_all_mon).mean(dim='time')

        # The area of 1-degree latitude band at the equator
earth_radius = 6371*1e3
equator_area = (3.14159*2*earth_radius)**2/360

# Create the weights

# The area of 1-degree latitude band at the equator
